 CLAUSES (INDEPENDENT VS. DEPENDENT)

You ever say something, then realize it made no damn sense until you added the second half? Thatâ€™s this tool. This is where you learn how thoughts hook together. What holds their weight. What leans. What falls over if you pull the string too hard.

ğŸ”— HOW IT CONNECTS
Youâ€™ve already felt the power of sentence length, fragments, and run-ons. Then you learned to build with simple and compound structuresâ€”one thought, or two thoughts linked.

Now we get into why some thoughts can stand alone and others need a partner. This is how sentences hang together. This is the balance of independence and dependence. Like relationships. Or comedy duos. Or sitcom roommates. One is a mess. The other pays the rent.

ğŸ§± WHATâ€™S A CLAUSE?
A clause is a group of words with a subject and a verb.

She dances.

Boom. Thatâ€™s a clause.

Now stick another verb in:

She dances when nobodyâ€™s watching.

Still one sentence. Two clauses.

Hereâ€™s the thing: not all clauses are equal. Some are independent. They can stand alone like full-grown adults. Others are dependentâ€”baby thoughts, unfinished. Theyâ€™re missing something. They need help to make sense.

ğŸ‘‘ INDEPENDENT CLAUSE
This is a full thought. A grown-ass sentence.

I donâ€™t trust him.
She laughed.
The lights flickered.

Each one can stand on its own. Clear. Strong. No babysitter needed.

You can chain these suckers together with conjunctions (and, but, or) or punctuation (semi-colons, periods, dashes).

I donâ€™t trust him, but I need the job.
She laughed; I didnâ€™t.

